Frequently Asked Questions
What is Neulasta used for? Neulasta (Pegfilgrastim) is primarily used to treat low white blood cell counts in cancer patients undergoing chemotherapy.

What are biosimilars? Biosimilars are biologic medical products highly similar to already approved reference biologics, with no significant differences in safety or efficacy.

What is the market value of the Neulasta biosimilars market? As of 2025, the market value for Neulasta biosimilars is projected to surpass USD 3 billion globally.

How does a biosimilar differ from a generic drug? Biosimilars are complex molecules derived from living cells, while generics are exact chemical copies of their reference products.

Why are biosimilars gaining popularity? Biosimilars offer a cost-effective alternative to expensive biologic treatments, making them an attractive option for healthcare providers and patients.

Are biosimilars safe? Yes, biosimilars must meet rigorous regulatory standards to ensure they are as safe and effective as their reference biologics.

Which regions are leading in the biosimilar market? North America, Europe, and the Asia-Pacific region are leading the global biosimilar market.

What are the key challenges for biosimilars? Patent litigation, regulatory hurdles, and market acceptance are major challenges faced by biosimilars.

How does Neulasta work in cancer treatment? Neulasta stimulates the production of white blood cells, helping reduce the risk of infection in chemotherapy patients.

What factors are driving the growth of the Neulasta biosimilar market? Increased demand for affordable biologics, rising cancer cases, and regulatory approvals for biosimilars are key growth drivers.

